	<div id="stars" class="modal hide fade" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="stars_label" aria-hidden="true">
	  <div class="modal-header">
	    <button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal" aria-hidden="true">×</button>
	    <h3 id="stars_label">KEPLER'S HEARTBEAT STARS</h3>
	  </div>
	  <div class="modal-body">
	    <p>As the Kepler scientists worked to find exoplanets revolving around the stars they made an unexpected finding: stars that revolve around each other. When planets orbit, gravity dictates their movement. With the stars, the story is the same. However, because stars are made of gas- gravity can distort their shape with more ease. Changes in eccentricity (how much the orbit around a body deviates from a perfect circle) leads to different amounts of time in periastron, the point of least separation between two stars, versus apastron, the point of greatest separation between two stars.</p>

		<p>KMD converts these data sets of Heartbeat star characteristics into sonifications that the user is instructed to move to. Movement during game play of each level describes a characteristic of the Heartbeat stars, such as gravity and mass.</p>

		<p>Astronomers conduct many theoretical computations. For the first time, the thought experiment that orbiting stars undergo RINGING when they cross close by to each other has finally been observed! NASAís Kepler Mission, with itís array of photoresistors has the ability to measure with the precision needed to find and record the 0.007% fluctuations in light that occur when stars ring.</p>

		<p>Kepler movementDash lets you play with the signal that astronomers use to show that their theory was true. Play through the game to learn about the features and computations the astronomers had to do in order to prove that their theory was reality.</p>
	  </div>
